        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1985-10-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1985-10-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="334"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d334">
                <head>334. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1"
                        >Shultz</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1"
                        >Reagan</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d334fn1">Source: Reagan Library, <persName
                            corresp="#p_SGP_1">George Shultz</persName> Papers, President’s Evening
                        Reading, July–December 1985. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1985-10-22">October 22, 1985</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1. <hi rend="italic">John Whitehead’s Meetings in Tunisia</hi>. In meetings with
                    the Tunisian Foreign Minister, Prime Minister and President <persName
                        corresp="#p_BH_4">Bourguiba</persName>,<note n="2" xml:id="d334fn2">A record
                        of <persName corresp="#p_WJ_1">Whitehead</persName>’s meetings is in
                        telegram 9713 from Tunis, October 22. (Reagan Library, Near East and South
                        Asia Affairs Directorate, Tunisia 1985 (10/07/1985–12/11/1985))</note> John
                    got an earful of Tunisian indignation about our perceived involvement in the
                    Israeli raid on the <gloss target="#t_PLO_1">PLO</gloss> base in Tunisia and our
                    reaction to it. As the day went on, however, the atmosphere of bitterness and
                    resentment seemed to steadily improve. Although the Tunisians are pessimistic
                    about the peace process and continue to be bitter toward Israel, all John’s
                    interlocutors made strong pledges of continued friendship and cooperation with
                    the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>. Significantly, they agreed that they
                    will not allow <persName corresp="#p_AAMZ_1">Abu Abbas</persName> into the
                    country as long as there is any doubt at all about his involvement in the
                        hijacking.<note n="3" xml:id="d334fn3">See <ref target="#d333">Document
                            333</ref>.</note> All indications are that the Tunisians consider the
                    mission to have been a success. (<gloss target="#t_S_1">S</gloss>)</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to Tunisia.]</p>
            </div>
